EventAction_Message.Text:
Sir, we are getting a message from headquarters:

 

COLONEL, we congratulate you on a successful mission.  To you and to those under your command, we offer the thanks of a grateful nation.

Sir, we are getting a message from headquarters.  They do not sound very happy with us:

 

COLONEL, you have failed to complete your mission.  Contact HQ immediately to receive new instructions.  Be prepared to face a Board of Inquiry where you will be expected to explain your actions.

Sir, we are getting a message from headquarters:

 

Captain, someone in your ao has fired on neutrals.  If your forces were responsible, you will have to face a Board of Inquiry and explain your actions.

 

------------------------

 

Oh, good.  Someone shot down a civilian aircraft.  It was probably carrying passengers.  Maybe even nuns and orphans.  Excellent!  Just the sort of thing the government wants to see on the front page of the London Times.

 

(Because Command only determines if a target has been destroyed and not who is responsible, but I assume the players are the "good guys" and would regret any loss of innocent life, I generally set up scenarios so the player will lose points any time a neutral target is destroyed.)

EventAction_Message.Description: Message for new ground unit destroyed
EventAction_Message.Text:
Sir, we are getting a message from headquarters:

 

COLONEL, someone in your ao has fired on neutrals.  If your forces were responsible, you will have to face a Board of Inquiry and explain your actions.
You just destroyed a school.  You need to be more careful.
You just destroyed a hotel.  You need to be more careful.

Okay, in fairness, it was probably hard to avoid blowing up the terminal when you're trying to wipe out pretty much everything else in the airport.  Even so, you probably just killed a lot of innocent civilians.  You need to be more careful.
You just destroyed a hospital.  You need to be more careful.

Command provides players wth a number of choices.  One of the most important choices is how much to manage groups and/or individual units oneself.  In many cases, it is better to create missions (i.e., sets of instructions that units and/or groups can follow automatically) and assign units and/or groups to those missions.

One option is to create a Patrol Mission.  In this case, it will be an air patrol mission (sometimes called CAP, or Combat Air Patrol).  To do this, start by holding down the CTRL key and right clicking your mouse.  You will get a small on screen menu.  Select Define Area.  When you do you, the pointer will turn into a little hand icon.  Hold down the left button on the mouse and drag this across part of the screen and you will get four reference points.  You can use these to set up a patrol zone. 

Now use Missions + Ref. Points --> Add New Mission.  Select Patrol and AAW Patrol.  Click okay and this will send you to another mission design screen with various other options.  There are a lot of options here and the best way to learn is simply through trial and error.  Keep in mind that the more detailed instructions you provide the more likely it is that your units (in this case, aircraft) will do what you want them to instead of trying to think for themselves.   

Another option for a scenario like this is to use the Mission Editor to create a Strike Mission. 

First, select Entebbe Airport.  Then, go to Missions + Ref. Points --> Add New Mission.  A mission design menu will pop up.  You want to select Strike and Land Strike.  Then give the mission a name, perhaps something original like "Entebbe Airport Strike."  Again, once you have done this, you will be sent to another design menu where you can complete the other details of the mission.

Ah, good, you've spotted something in the air. 

Kill it!  Kill it with fire!

Umm...no, wait.  Perhaps it would be best to first identify it and make sure it isn't something you don't want to blow up, like a civilian airliner full of nuns and orphans.  You know, just to be on the safe side. 

If you are sure you know what a potential target is, you can mark it Hostile by selecting it and typing the H key, Unfriendly by using the U key, Neutral by using the N key, or Friendly by using the F key.  This can be especially useful if you already know a target is hostile and want to automatically attack before your adversary can identify your units as hostile. 

It is also useful if you have units on a patrol mission and they are trying to intercept a distant target because they do not know what it is--if you know it is just a fishing boat or something like that, identify it as Neutral and the units you have on patrol will go back to investgiating other contacts that might actually need to be intercepted.

Sir, Bell #2 has completed its reconnaissance mission and is requesting permission to return to base.

What are your orders, Sir?

Sir, Bell #1 has completed its reconnaissance mission and is requesting permission to return to base.

What are your orders, Sir?

Sir, we're getting reports that the State House in Entebbe has been destroyed.  If the reports are accurate, we have severely damaged Ugandan command and control capabilities in Entebbe.

What are your orders, Sir?

--------------------------------------------------------------

Good work!  You have destroyed an important target, one of the centers of government in Entebbe.

EventAction_Message.Description: Message for water treatment plant destroyed
EventAction_Message.Text:
Sir, we are getting reports that the water treatment plant in Entebbe has been destroyed.  If the reports are accurate, we have seriously damaged the infrastructure of the city.  It is going to cost them a lot to fix that, and that's exactly the kind of message Whitehall wanted to send President Amin.

What are your orders, Sir?

Sir, we have reports that we have destroyed a Ugandan AAA gun.

What are your orders, Sir?

Ah, good, you've spotted something in the air. 

Kill it!  Kill it with fire!

Ummm...okay, you probably know what I'm going to say here.  Make sure you are pretty sure you know what something is before you shoot at it.  That's just general good advice.

By now, you probably have some of your fighters in the air.  Time to do a little thinking about how to win the air war.

You can get a lot of information about the aircraft in a scenario with the database (Game --> Database Viewer). 

Your primary fighter (unless you want to take the time to arm all of your Phantoms for air-to-air missions) is the Lighting. 

The Lightning has a manueverability rating of 2.5.  The Red Top missile has a range of 16 miles.  The MiG-21's main missile, the AA-2 Atoll, only has a range of four miles, but the Mig-21 has a manueverability rating of 3.  That means once the aircraft are close to each other, a MiG-21 can win the dogfight. 

One advantage is experience, which Command does model.  Uganda has been rated overall at Cadet level.  The U.K. has been rated, overall, at Regular level, and some of the Lightnings are rated at Veteran level, meaning their pilots have above average training and experience. 

You do have a few Phantoms, which are even more manueverable than the MiG-21, although not by much, and which have Sparrow missiles.  This should help you even the odds.

One technique that might prove useful is an ambush.  Get the MiGs to follow one group of your aircraft and then use another group to get behind them and kill them.
